<p>A <b>credit card</b> is part of a system of <a href="/wiki/Payment" title="Payment">payments</a> named after the small <a href="/wiki/Plastic" title="Plastic">plastic</a> card issued to users of the system. It is a card entitling its holder to buy goods and services based on the holder's promise to pay for these goods and services.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The issuer of the card grants a <a href="/wiki/Line_of_credit" title="Line of credit">line of credit</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Consumer" title="Consumer">consumer</a> (or the user) from which the user can borrow money for payment to a <a href="/wiki/Merchant" title="Merchant">merchant</a> or as a <a href="/wiki/Cash_advance" title="Cash advance">cash advance</a> to the user.</p>
<p>A credit card is different from a <a href="/wiki/Charge_card" title="Charge card">charge card</a>, where a charge card requires the balance to be paid in full each month. In contrast, credit cards allow the consumers to 'revolve' their balance, at the cost of having <a href="/wiki/Credit_card_interest" title="Credit card interest">interest</a> charged. Most credit cards are issued by local <a href="/wiki/Bank" title="Bank">banks</a> or <a href="/wiki/Credit_union" title="Credit union">credit unions</a>, and are the shape and size specified by the <a href="/wiki/ISO/IEC_7810" title="ISO/IEC 7810">ISO/IEC 7810</a> standard as ID-1.</p>
